John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of service in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with a series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the entire community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for continuing and higher education, their career and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects at excellent levels within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t rely only on English when we want to build relationships and a trust bond with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can derive that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score (“A”) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students in German, 69 percent of students in French and 63 percent of students in Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now as much appreciated as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A study by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that of the obstacles to fill jobs 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language knowledge, according to employers.
Language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future career.
Now that more and more jobs require language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage in competition.
According to a YouGov poll, among more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language to speak above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Several languages can speak, especially those of emerging economies, will offer children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK as they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed regardless of the future.
It cannot currently be denied that languages remain vital in a global business environment for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered to be “International communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
