National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a property in the Scottish highlands tries to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will let new light shine on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the usual and small dwarf bat, the brown large butterfly mouse and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the property to track the activities of the bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NTS and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cry of the bat and what kind of thing it does.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to create a detailed image on landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS’ Nature Protection Advisor, hopes that the results show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making pasture fields and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Fleet mouse populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, such as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by house cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, their nightly hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
In the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, inspect sleeping places, and sometimes carry out rescue actions.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the three-story property in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten species of bats live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
“Here in Threeve we have a great environment for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much about bats not yet known and therefore the work we do here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to be able to thrive.
He emphasizes the importance of control of bats before maintenance activities are carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boys, possibly destroying a full local population.
Fleet mice are a protected species of animals and it is illegal to kill them, to fall into trouble or to disrupt or destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said: “We still have to learn a lot about our bats and many of our species simply don’t know how their populations are doing.
